## TigerBeetle's Multiple-Constructor Patterns in Zig

TigerBeetle uses several distinct, idiomatic strategies to handle multiple constructors for structs. Here's a full taxonomy with real examples from the codebase.

---

### Pattern 1: `init` as a Default-Argument Shortcut Delegating to `init_<variant>`

The canonical pattern: `init` calls `init_<param>` with a sensible default, while `init_<param>` exposes the full parameterization. The suffix names the *extra parameter* that varies.

**[`ZipfianGenerator`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/zipfian.zig#L83-L101)** — `init` vs `init_theta`:
```zig
/// Create a generator from `[0, items)` with `theta` equal to 0.99.
pub fn init(items: u64) ZipfianGenerator {
    return ZipfianGenerator.init_theta(items, theta_default);
}

/// Create a generator from `[0, items)` with given `theta`.
pub fn init_theta(items: u64, theta: f64) ZipfianGenerator {
    assert(theta > 0.0);
    assert(theta != 1.0);
    return ZipfianGenerator{ .theta = theta, .n = items, .zetan = zeta(items, theta) };
}
```

**[`ZipfianShuffled`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/zipfian.zig#L194-L207)** — same pattern applied to the shuffled variant:
```zig
pub fn init(items: u64, prng: *stdx.PRNG) ZipfianShuffled {
    return ZipfianShuffled.init_theta(items, theta_default, prng);
}

pub fn init_theta(items: u64, theta: f64, prng: *stdx.PRNG) ZipfianShuffled { ... }
```

The tests even explicitly document this shape with a comment: `// Test that ctors are all doing the same thing.`

---

### Pattern 2: `init` vs `init_<qualifier>` for Different Construction *Modes*

When two constructors represent fundamentally *different ways to build* the same struct (not just a default parameter), the suffix describes the *mode*, not just the extra parameter.

**[`MessagePool`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/message_pool.zig#L194-L230)** — `init` (from a role-typed Options) vs `init_capacity` (raw number of messages):
```zig
pub fn init(
    allocator: mem.Allocator,
    options: Options,        // typed enum: .replica or .client — computes count internally
) error{OutOfMemory}!MessagePool {
    return MessagePool.init_capacity(allocator, options.messages_max());
}

pub fn init_capacity(
    allocator: mem.Allocator,
    messages_max: u32,       // raw capacity, bypasses role-based calculation
) error{OutOfMemory}!MessagePool { ... }
```
`init` is the production path; `init_capacity` is called by `init` internally but also used by tests that need a fixed-size pool (e.g., [`ReplySequence`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/testing/reply_sequence.zig)).

**[`StatsD`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/trace/statsd.zig#L131-L181)** — `init_udp` vs `init_log`: there is *no* bare `init` at all; each constructor name fully describes what it builds:
```zig
/// Creates a statsd instance, which will send UDP packets via the IO instance provided.
pub fn init_udp(
    allocator: std.mem.Allocator,
    process_id: ProcessID,
    io: *IO,
    address: std.net.Address,
) !StatsD { ... }

// Creates a statsd instance, which will log out the packets that would have been sent.
// Useful so that all of the other code can run and be tested in the simulator.
pub fn init_log(
    allocator: std.mem.Allocator,
    process_id: ProcessID,
) !StatsD { ... }
```
Note the `io` and `address` parameters disappear entirely in `init_log` — this is a true fork, not a default. There is no `init` because neither mode is more "default" than the other.

---

### Pattern 3: `init_empty` and `open_empty` — Lifecycle-State Constructors

For structs with explicit lifecycle state (e.g., "opened" vs "closed"), TigerBeetle adds a lifecycle qualifier *and* sometimes a state qualifier.

**[`FreeSet`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/free_set.zig#L115-L265)**:
```zig
// Production path: full configuration struct.
pub fn init(allocator: mem.Allocator, options: struct {
    grid_size_limit: usize,
    blocks_released_prior_checkpoint_durability_max: usize,
}) !FreeSet { ... }

// A shortcut to initialize an empty free set for tests.
// Leaves `opened = false`.
pub fn init_empty(allocator: mem.Allocator, blocks_count: usize) !FreeSet {
    comptime assert(constants.verify);
    var set = try init(allocator, .{ ... });
    // ...
}

// A shortcut to initialize AND open an empty free set for tests.
// Sets `opened = true` and `checkpoint_durable = true`.
pub fn open_empty(allocator: mem.Allocator, blocks_count: usize) !FreeSet {
    comptime assert(constants.verify);
    var set = try init(allocator, .{ ... });
    set.open(.{ ... });
    set.checkpoint_durable = true;
    // ...
}
```

The constructor comments are explicit: `// A shortcut to initialize an empty free set for tests.` Both `init_empty` and `open_empty` are guarded by `comptime assert(constants.verify)` — they are test-only helpers and that is enforced at compile time.

---

### Pattern 4: `from_seed` vs `from_seed_testing` — Environment-Scoped Constructors

**[`PRNG`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/prng.zig#L110-L123)**:
```zig
pub fn from_seed(seed: u64) PRNG {
    var s = seed;
    return .{ .s = .{
        split_mix_64(&s), split_mix_64(&s),
        split_mix_64(&s), split_mix_64(&s),
    } };
}

pub fn from_seed_testing() PRNG {
    comptime assert(@import("builtin").is_test);   // ← compile-time test gate
    return .from_seed(std.testing.random_seed);
}
```

The `_testing` suffix carries both semantic meaning ("this is for tests") and a compile-time enforcement — calling it in non-test code is a compile error. Note the prefix is `from_` rather than `init_`, which is also pattern 6 below.

---

### Pattern 5: Comptime-Dispatched `init` via `pub const` Alias

**[`RingBufferType`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig#L35-L52)** — the "constructor" is selected at *compile time* based on the type parameter, resolving to completely different function signatures. The caller always calls `.init(...)` but gets a different function:

```zig
pub const init = switch (buffer_type) {
    .array => init_array,   // fn() RingBuffer        — no allocator
    .slice => init_slice,   // fn(Allocator, usize) !RingBuffer — needs allocator + capacity
};

fn init_array() RingBuffer {
    comptime assert(buffer_type == .array);
    return .{ .buffer = undefined };
}

fn init_slice(allocator: mem.Allocator, capacity: usize) !RingBuffer {
    comptime assert(buffer_type == .slice);
    assert(capacity > 0);
    const buffer = try allocator.alloc(T, capacity);
    return RingBuffer{ .buffer = buffer };
}
```

Usage:
```zig
// Array-backed (capacity known at comptime, no allocator):
var array_ring = RingBufferType(u32, .{ .array = 2 }).init();

// Slice-backed (capacity at runtime, requires allocator):
var pointer_ring = try RingBufferType(u32, .slice).init(testing.allocator, 2);
```

This is an elegant Zig-specific trick: the `init` name is unified for the caller, but the *type* of `init` (and thus its parameter list) differs. The `comptime assert` in each private function ensures the dispatch table is correct.

---

### Pattern 6: `from_<source>` Naming for Conversion Constructors

When a constructor builds a struct *from* a different representation (not just allocating fresh), TigerBeetle uses `from_` as the prefix instead of `init_`.

**[`PRNG`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/prng.zig#L110-L123)**: `from_seed(u64)` vs `from_seed_testing()` — see pattern 4 above.

**[`InstantUnix`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/time_units.zig#L215-L224)**:
```zig
pub fn now() InstantUnix { ... }                        // from the OS clock

pub fn from_timestamp_s(timestamp_s: u64) InstantUnix { // from a Unix timestamp in seconds
    return InstantUnix{ .ns = timestamp_s * std.time.ms_per_s * std.time.ns_per_ms };
}
```

**[`BoundedArrayType`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/bounded_array.zig#L15-L23)**:
```zig
pub inline fn from_slice(items: []const T) error{Overflow}!BoundedArray {
    if (items.len <= buffer_capacity) {
        var result: BoundedArray = .{};
        result.push_slice(items);
        return result;
    } else {
        return error.Overflow;
    }
}
```

**[`Duration`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/time_units.zig#L29-L43)** also uses unit-named constructors (not `init_`, not `from_`, just the unit name as the function):
```zig
pub fn us(amount_us: u64) Duration { ... }
pub fn ms(amount_ms: u64) Duration { ... }
pub fn seconds(amount_seconds: u64) Duration { ... }
pub fn minutes(amount_minutes: u64) Duration { ... }
```

---

### Pattern 7: `init_<component>` for Module-Level Fixture Functions

In [`src/testing/fixtures.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/testing/fixtures.zig), the constructors are *module-level* functions (not struct methods), and they use the `init_<type>` naming to signal "this constructs a `<type>`". The file's design doc explains this explicitly:

```zig
pub fn init_time(options: struct {
    resolution: u64 = constants.tick_ms * std.time.ns_per_ms,
    offset_type: OffsetType = .linear,
    offset_coefficient_A: i64 = 0,
    // ...
}) TimeSim { ... }

pub fn init_tracer(gpa: std.mem.Allocator, init: Time, options: struct {
    writer: ?std.io.AnyWriter = null,
    process_id: Tracer.ProcessID = .{ .replica = ... },
}) !Tracer { ... }

pub fn init_storage(gpa: std.mem.Allocator, options: Storage.Options) !Storage { ... }

pub fn init_superblock(gpa: std.mem.Allocator, storage: *Storage, options: struct {
    storage_size_limit: ?u64 = null,
}) !SuperBlock { ... }

pub fn init_grid(gpa: std.mem.Allocator, trace: *Tracer, superblock: *SuperBlock, options: struct {
    missing_blocks_max: u64 = 0,
    missing_tables_max: u64 = 0,
    // ...
}) !Grid { ... }
```

The file's module-level comment spells out the conventions:
> - All functions take struct options as a last argument, even if it starts out as empty.
> - Most options should have defaults. […] for tests, all options that are set are meaningful for a particular test.
> - All dependent fixtures are passed in positionally because they can't be defaulted and their types are unique.

---

### Summary Table

| Pattern | Naming Convention | Key Characteristic |
|---|---|---|
| Default + full | `init` delegates to `init_<param>` | `init` is a convenience wrapper |
| Mode fork | `init_<mode>` (no bare `init`) | Different backends; neither is the "default" |
| Lifecycle state | `init_empty`, `open_empty` | Suffix encodes post-construction state |
| Environment scoped | `from_seed` vs `from_seed_testing` | `_testing` suffix + `comptime assert(is_test)` |
| Comptime dispatch | `pub const init = switch (...)` | Caller writes `.init(...)`, function signature varies by type |
| Conversion | `from_<source>` or unit name | Constructing from a different representation |
| Module fixtures | free functions `init_<Type>` | Used in `testing/fixtures.zig` for shared test setup |

The overarching principle: **names describe the variation, not just the existence of alternatives**. `init_theta`, `init_capacity`, `init_udp`, `init_log`, `init_empty`, `open_empty`, `from_seed`, `from_seed_testing` — each name tells you *what differs* about that constructor versus the others.

